ire, England"},"cs":{"about 1360–":"okolo 1360–Zesnulý","1385–Female":"1385–Zesnulá","1360–Male":"1360–Zesnulý","about 1360":"okolo 1360","1455":"1455","1385":"1385","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, Anglie"},"da":{"about 1360–":"omkring 1360–Afdød","1385–Female":"1385–Afdød","1360–Male":"1360–Afdød","about 1360":"omkring 1360","1455":"1455","1385":"1385","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England"},"nl":{"about 1360–":"circa 1360–Overleden","1385–Female":"1385–Overleden","1360–Male":"1360–Overleden","about 1360":"circa 1360","1455":"1455","1385":"1385","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England"},"en":{"about 1360–":"about 1360–Deceased","1385–Female":"1385–Deceased","1360–Male":"1360–Deceased","about 1360":"about 1360","1455":"1455","1385":"1385","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Corbett","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (West Midlands, of Norman origin): nickname from Old French <i>corbet</i> ‘raven’, probably denoting someone with dark hair or a dark complexion.","History: This is the name of a family descended from Hugh <i>Corbet</i>, a Norman baron who settled in Shropshire following the Norman Conquest. One of his descendants, Sir Richard Corbet, was granted land near Shrewsbury in 1223; since the 13th century, this place has been known as Moreton Corbet. The name was taken from Shropshire to Scotland in the 12th century and to northern Ireland in the 17th century, and thence to North America by at least one group of bearers of the name."],"variants":[{"name":"Corbit","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Corbett  . This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Corb","meanings":["English (Durham): nickname from Middle English <i>corb</i> ‘raven’ (from Old French <i>corb</i>; compare   Corbett  ,   Corbin  )."]},{"name":"Corbet","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Corbett  .","History: Walter Corbet, a royal knight in 12th-century Scotland, was the first of that name in that kingdom. His 13th-century descendants were major landholders in the Borders, and in the 14th century they acquired lands in the North of Scotland."]},{"name":"Corbitt","meanings":["English: variant of   Corbett  .","Irish: variant of   Corban  ."]},{"name":"Corban","meanings":["Irish: shortened Anglicized form of <b>Ó Corbáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Corbán</i>’ or <b>Ó Coirbín</b> ‘descendant of <i>Coirbín</i>’, both possibly from an occupational name based on <i>corb</i> ‘chariot’. Both names have also been Anglicized as   Corbett  .","Irish: alternatively, a variant of <b>Currivan</b>, from <b>Ó Coirbheáin</b>, itself a variant of   Corban   (pronounced with three syllables in Irish).","Romanian: nickname derived from <i>corb</i> ‘crow’, with the augmentative suffix <i>-an</i>."]}]},{"name":"Roberti","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Germanic.  See  <b>Robert</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":22,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705197,"age":95,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url"